<TEXT>
   The Brooklyn Museum, Brooklyn, N.Y.: "The Intimate
Interiors of Edouard Vuillard" -- The first major exhibition
in nearly 20 years devoted to Vuillard, whose jewel-like
paintings depict scenes from 19th-century bourgeois life. The
more than 100 paintings and works on paper include
self-portraits, family scenes, paintings of seamstresses and
portraits of the artist's intimate, the salon-keeper Misia
Natanson. 200 Eastern Parkway, May 18-July 30.
                                                                                                       

   The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York: "Masterworks of
Louis Comfort Tiffany" -- Windows, lamps, mosaics, ceramics,
bronzes, paintings and jewelry by this master glassmaker. The
show includes some of Tiffany's earliest experiments with
Favrile glass and leaded glass shades, as well as such
opulent later creations as the "Helen Gould Landscape
Window." More than 5,000 pieces of glass were used to create
this 11-foot panel, depicting a fawn drinking at a stream.
82nd Street and Fifth Avenue, through Sept. 9.
                                                                                                       

   Place des Antiquaires, New York: "Chinnery &amp; The China
Coast-Paintings from the Collection of The Hongkong and
Shanghai Bank" -- A first-ever exhibition of 70 paintings by
19th-century artists working in South China. Unknown Chinese
artists are represented here along with Europeans such as
George Chinnery, an English portraitist and draughtsman.
Works include portraits of English traders and their lavish
estates, Hong Kong merchants, and scenes from Asian life and
trade. 125 E. 57th St., through June 2. (Monday through
Saturday, 11-6). The show then leaves the country for
Luxembourg and London.
                                                                                                       

   Yale Center for British Art, New Haven, Conn.: "Powder
Celestial: Snuff Boxes, 1700-1880" -- Men and women in all
walks of life indulged in snuff, as a survey of the 300-odd
European boxes collected here shows. The flasks, mulls and
boxes are fashioned out of everything from wood, papier-mache
and coquilla nut to tortoise shell, ivory, agate and straw.
1080 Chapel St., through June 24.
                                                                                                       

   PHOTOGRAPHY
                                                                                                       

   International Center of Photography Midtown, New York:
"Lee Miller: Photographer" -- This fashion model, war
correspondent, world traveler and chef also knew what to do
with a camera. The 96 photographs on view here include
powerful images from Ms. Miller's stint with the U.S. Army
during World War II along with early surrealist photos and
revealing portraits of Pablo Picasso, Man Ray and other
friends. 1133 Avenue of the Americas, through June 10. The
show then moves to the Art Institute of Chicago, June 23-Aug.
26; Santa Monica Museum of Art, Sept. 8-Nov. 4; The Rochester
Institute of Technology, Rochester, N.Y., Nov. 12-Dec. 2.
                                                                                                       

   DANCE
                                                                                                       

   Parsons Dance Company: As a Paul Taylor dancer, David
Parsons always stood out from the pack with his witty
athleticism, his nonchalant virtuosity. Now his own fledgling
troupe is starting to do the same. The company shows why in
its first major New York season, tonight through May 20.
Among the three premieres scheduled are "Nascimento," a lush
ensemble work to an original score by Brazilian composer
Milton Nascimento; and "Elysian Fields," an exploration of
violence that features Parsons as a deceptively
angelic-looking demon. Joyce Theater, 175 Eighth Ave. (at
19th Street). 212-242-0800.
                                                                                                       

   MUSIC
                                                                                                       

   Minnesota Opera, Minnesota: The world premiere of Libby
Larsen's "Frankenstein, The Modern Prometheus" on May 25
retells Mary Shelley's sad story of the manmade monster who
searches for love and understanding in a cruel world. Dale
Johnson conducts a cast including Steven Tharp as Dr. Victor
Frankenstein and Tom Schumacher as the monster. World
Theater, 10 East Exchange St., St. Paul, Minn. 612-298-1300.
                                                                                                       

   Charleston, S.C.: The Spoleto Festival U.S.A. starts off
on May 25 with a gala performance of Beethoven's Seventh
conducted by Leonard Bernstein. The 114-event festival
includes a new production of Wagner's "Parsifal," directed by
Gian Carlo Menotti, and the world premiere of a multimedia
piece by Philip Glass, Allen Ginsberg and Jerome Sirlin, "The
Hydrogen Jukebox." Dance, chamber music and theater are also
featured this season, which closes on June 10. To order
tickets by phone call 800-868-7228 or 803-577-4500.
                                                                                                       

   Greenwich House, New York: Friends &amp; Enemies of New Music
celebrates its first season with a concert offering new works
by, among others, Nancy Gunn and Tom Cipullo. 27 Barrow St.
212-874-4814.
                                                                                                       

   3 Mustaphas 3: Though their origins are more British than
Balkan, this fez-sporting sextet serves up a spicy musical
goulash. Expect to hear some of the wild and wooly material
from their current release, "Heart of Uncle" (Rykodisc),
which mingles styles from Southern Europe, the Middle East,
Africa, the Caribbean and beyond, way beyond -- New York
(Lone Star Roadhouse), May 15; Washington, D.C. (The Ritz),
May 16; Baltimore (8 X 10), May 17; Tampa, Fla. (Cuban Club),
May 19; Winston-Salem, N.C. (Mayfest), May 20;
Charlottesville, Va. (Trax), May 21; Toronto (The Diamond),
May 24; Chicago (Navy Pier Ballroom), May 27; San Francisco
(Slim's), May 29; Seattle (Backstage), June 1; Vancouver
(Commodore Ballroom), June 2.
